## Conclusion

The resistances to imperialism in Africa and India shared significant commonalities despite differing historical and cultural contexts. Both regions initially engaged in armed resistance that was ultimately undermined by European military superiority. Subsequently, they adopted nonviolent, political, economic, and cultural strategies to challenge colonial rule. Leadership by indigenous elites and intellectuals was pivotal in mobilizing resistance and articulating nationalist aspirations. Both faced challenges due to internal divisions exacerbated by colonial divide-and-rule tactics. Furthermore, global political developments and international institutions played supportive roles in their struggles for independence.

These shared features underscore a broader pattern of indigenous responses to imperialism characterized by resilience, adaptability, and a profound desire for self-determination. Understanding these commonalities enriches the historiography of anti-imperial movements and highlights the interconnectedness of global struggles against colonial domination.

